goals.question: What is the distribution of US_Gross and Worldwide_Gross?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of US_Gross vs Worldwide_Gross
goals.rationale: This will help us understand the relationship between the US and worldwide gross earnings of the movies. We can identify if there is a correlation between the two variables and if the movies that perform well in the US also perform well worldwide.

goals.question: What is the distribution of Production_Budget?
goals.rationale: This will help us understand the range of production budgets for the movies in the dataset. We can identify if there are any outliers and if there is a concentration of movies within a certain budget range.

goals.question: What is the distribution of IMDB_Rating and Rotten_Tomatoes_Rating?
goals.visualization: box plot of IMDB_Rating and Rotten_Tomatoes_Rating
goals.rationale: This will help us understand the distribution of ratings for the movies in the dataset. We can identify if there is a difference in the distribution of ratings between the two rating systems and if there are any outliers.

goals.question: What is the distribution of Running_Time_min?
goals.rationale: This will help us understand the range of running times for the movies in the dataset. We can identify if there are any outliers and if there is a concentration of movies within a certain running time range.

goals.question: What is the distribution of Major_Genre?
goals.rationale: This will help us understand the distribution of major genres for the movies in the dataset. We can identify if there is a concentration of movies within a certain genre and if there are any genres that are overrepresented or underrepresented in the dataset.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.scatterplot(data=data, x='US_Gross', y='Worldwide_Gross')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of US_Gross and Worldwide_Gross?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='Production_Budget', kde=True, color='blue')
    median_budget = data['Production_Budget'].median()
    plt.axvline(median_budget, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f'Median: {median_budget:.2f}')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of Production_Budget?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    sns.boxplot(data=data[['IMDB_Rating', 'Rotten_Tomatoes_Rating']], ax=ax)
    ax.set_title('What is the distribution of IMDB_Rating and Rotten_Tomatoes_Rating?')
    ax.legend(['IMDB_Rating', 'Rotten_Tomatoes_Rating'])
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Release_Date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Release_Date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['Release_Date'])]

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='Running_Time_min', bins=20, kde=True, color='blue', alpha=0.5)
    plt.axvline(data['Running_Time_min'].median(), color='red', linestyle='--', label=f"Median: {data['Running_Time_min'].median():.2f}")
    plt.xlabel('Running Time (minutes)')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of Running_Time_min?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    genre_counts = data['Major_Genre'].value_counts()
    sns.barplot(x=genre_counts.index, y=genre_counts.values)
    plt.xlabel('Major Genre')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title('What is the distribution of Major_Genre?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
